article.headline: Tigers need two wins to tie best start in school history
article.linkText: Third-ranked Tigers turn up heat on Penn State
article.story:
BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) -- Aiysha Smith and her teammates got just
what they wanted against Penn State -- a victory and some notice.  "A lot of people didn't know us," said Smith, who scored 22
points as LSU  (No. 3 ESPN/USA Today, No. 2 AP) stayed unbeaten with an 80-63 victory over  Penn State  (No. 14, 15). "They heard we were good, but they said we hadn't
beaten anybody good."

	   After winning seven of its first nine games against teams with
losing records, LSU (12-0) beat the nation's 15th-ranked team for
the second time in eight days. 

The Lady Tigers beat Texas 76-58 the
previous Saturday, dropping them from 15th to 17th. The Tigers are
now two wins away from tying the best start in school history,
which was 14-0 during the 1996-97 season.

	   LSU, with the nation's third-ranked scoring defense, held Penn
State 23 points below its average of 86 points a game. LSU also
scored 24 points off Penn State's 19 turnovers.

	   "Knowing the shooters this club has and what a big defensive
team they are, I thought this game was about defense, and it
probably was our best effort," said LSU coach Sue Gunter.

	   Ashli Schwab had 22 points and 11 rebounds to lead the Lady
Lions (10-3). Tanisha Wright added 18 points. Kelly Mazzante, the
nation's third-leading scorer at 27.2 points per game, was held to
13.

	   "Mazzante is a great player and we just had to contain her,"
said Doneeka Hodges, who guarded Mazzante most of the game. "We
knew she would get some shots off but just wanted to make sure we
contested everything she put up."

	   Seimone Augustus and Ke-Ke Tardy each added 11 points for LSU,
while Smith had nine rebounds.

	   The Tigers greater depth was apparent. LSU got 29 points from
its bench, compared to 3 points for Penn State.

	   "We have a lot of depth and we try not to have any drop-off
when people come off the bench," Roneeka Hodges said.

	   LSU held its annual "Pack the PMAC" promotion for the game,
selling $1 tickets and attracting 9,798 fans at the Pete Maravich
Assembly Center -- the largest turnout ever for women's basketball
in Louisiana. It broke the record of 9,636 set in the Auburn-LSU
game in 2001.

	   The victory put LSU coach Sue Gunter three shy of 400 for her
career with the Lady Tigers.

	   LSU led 5-0 and never trailed. The Lady Tigers led 38-28 at
halftime and outshot Penn State 55 percent to 41 percent in the
first half. LSU's defense cause the Lady Lions problems throughout
the game.

	   LSU also scored 16 points off fast breaks, compared with six for
Penn State.
